Iraqis faced escalating violence as they prepared to vote in a historic election.
Insurgents targeted polling stations and security forces, resulting in numerous casualties.
Despite threats and attacks, US President Bush encouraged Iraqis to seize the opportunity to vote.
The tension was palpable as ballot boxes were distributed amidst destruction and fear.
The Al-Qaeda-linked group vowed to continue attacks even after the election.
Security measures were heightened, but suicide bombings and shootings persisted.
The day before the election saw multiple incidents, including a suicide bombing that claimed innocent lives.
Despite the risks, Iraqis were determined to exercise their right to vote in the face of adversity.
